# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anke-fuchs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] As a matriculation examination, *Abitur* can be compared to A levels, the *Matura*, the Bagrut certificate or the International Baccalaureate Diploma, which are all ranked as level 4 in the European Qualifications Framework.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Thus, it encompasses the functions of both a school graduation certificate and a college entrance exam.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Abitur confers *Allgemeine Hochschulreife* (allows students to enter university or Fachhochschule), while there are other ways of obtaining it.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In 2005, some 231,000 students obtained *Allgemeine Hochschulreife* in Germany.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] This number rose over time to around 263,000 in 2021.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Of those, most obtained their *Allgemeine Hochschulreife* at a Gymnasium, while 40,000 received it at a different kind of school, such as a Gesamtschulen.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] If those who obtain the *Fachhochschulreife* (144,399 in 2012) are also added, then the total of those who obtained the right to study at a university or a *Fachhochschule* is 395,000 (2021).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Until the eighteenth century, every German university had its own entrance examination.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In 1788 Prussia introduced the *Abiturreglement*, a law, for the first time within Germany, establishing the *Abitur* as an official qualification.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] It was later also established in the other German states.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In 1834, it became the only university entrance exam in Prussia, and it remained so in all states of Germany until 1998.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Since then, the German state of Hesse allows students with *Fachhochschulreife* (see below) to study at the universities within that state.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The academic level of the *Abitur* is comparable to the International Baccalaureate, the GCE Advanced Level and the Advanced Placement tests.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The study requirements for the International Baccalaureate differ little from the German exam requirements.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] It is the only school-leaving certificate in all states of Germany that allows the graduate (or *Abiturient*) to move directly to university.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The other school leaving certificates, the *Hauptschulabschluss* and the *Realschulabschluss*, do not allow their holders to matriculate at a university.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Those granted certificates of *Hauptschulabschluss* or *Realschulabschluss* can gain a specialized *Fachhochschulreife* or an *Abitur* if they graduate from a *Berufsschule* and then attend *Berufsoberschule* or graduate from a *Fachoberschule*.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] However, the *Abitur* is not the only path to university studies, as some universities set up their own entrance examinations.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Students who successfully passed a "Begabtenprüfung" ("aptitude test") are also eligible.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Students from other countries who hold a high school graduate certificate that is not counted as equivalent to the *Abitur* (such as the American high school diploma) and who do well enough on the ACT or SAT test, may also enter German universities.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] A person who does not hold the *Abitur* and did not take an aptitude test may still be admitted to university by completing at least the 10th grade and doing well on an IQ test (see: Hochbegabtenstudium).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In German, the European Baccalaureate is called *europäisches Abitur*, and the International Baccalaureate is called *internationales Abitur*, neither to be confused with the German *Abitur*.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The French-German Baccalaureate is called *deutsch-französisches Abitur*, and is equivalent both to the German Abitur and to the French Baccalauréat.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The term *Fachabitur* was used in all of Western Germany for a variation of the *Abitur* until the 1990s; the official term for the German qualification is *fachgebundene Hochschulreife*.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] This qualification includes only one foreign language (usually, English).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The *Abitur*, in contrast, usually requires two foreign languages.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The *Fachabitur* also allows the graduate to start studying at a university but is limited to a specified range of majors, depending on the specific subjects covered in his *Fachabitur* examinations.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] But the graduate is allowed to study for all majors at a *Fachhochschule* (University of Applied Sciences, in some ways comparable to polytechnics).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Today, the school leaving certificate is called *fachgebundenes Abitur* ('restricted subject *Abitur*').
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The term *Fachabitur* substitutes in most parts of Germany for the *Fachhochschulreife (FHR)*.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] It was introduced in West Germany in the 1970s together with the *Fachhochschulen*.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] It enables the graduate to start studying at a *Fachhochschule* and, in Hesse, also at a university within that state.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In the Gymnasiums of some states it is awarded in the year before the *Abitur* is reached.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] However, the normal way to obtain *Fachhochschulreife* is graduation from a German *Fachoberschule*, a vocational high school, also introduced in the 1970s.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The term *Notabitur* ('emergency *Abitur*') describes a qualification used only during World War I and World War II.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The *Notabitur* during World War I included an examination, roughly equivalent to the *Abitur* exam.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The World War II *Notabitur*, in contrast, was granted without an examination.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] After the war this was a major disadvantage for the students concerned since, unlike its World War I counterpart, the certificate was generally not recognised in West Germany and never recognised in East Germany.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Universities requested the *Abitur* to consist of written exams including at least two foreign languages (almost always Latin and French, the latter sometimes replaced by English).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Students, who received the *Notabitur* during World War II were offered to re-enter school to prepare for and take the exam after the war had ended.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Those special *Abitur* preparation classes were made up of young adults of different age and sex, which was very unusual at the time.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In Australia, the graduation certificate awarded to high school students is the Senior Secondary Certificate of Education (SSCE).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] However, the name of the SSCE varies from state to state.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In Victoria, it is called the Victorian Certificate of Education (VCE); in New South Wales it is called the Higher Schools Certificate (HSC).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In India various states name it differently.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Each Indian state has its own examination board, some individual states having their own entrance test system.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Passing the specified examination qualifies the student to enter into undergraduate program in a university.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] For example, in the states of Andhra Pradesh and Telangana this is known as Board of Intermediate Examination (BIE).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] For professional, specialist programs and well reputed institutions there are entrance tests.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] For engineering there is a Joint Engineering Entrance Joint Entrance Examination conducted at all India level.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] For medical undergraduate MBBS programs there is a national eligibility and entrance test known as NEET-UG National Eligibility and Entrance Test conducted at all of India.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] There is also an all India level examination conducted by Central Board of Secondary education CBSE the certification is known as Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] During the final examinations (*Abiturprüfungen*), students are tested in four or five subjects (at least one of which is oral).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Occasionally, schools (especially *berufsorientierte Gymnasien*) offer vocational subjects such as pedagogy, business informatics, biotechnology and mechanical engineering.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Final exams are usually taken from March to May or June.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Papers are graded by at least two teachers at the school.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Before reunification, *Abitur* exams were given locally in West Germany, but Bavaria has conducted centralized exams (*Zentralabitur*) since 1854.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] After reunification, most states of the former East Germany continued centralized exams, and at the beginning of the 21st century, many states adopted centralized exams.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In 2013, all other states except Rheinland-Pfalz also introduced centralized written exams at least in the core subjects (German, mathematics and the first foreign language, usually English).
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The *Kultusministerkonferenz* (KMK) of several states expanded the exams to scientific subjects and the social sciences.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The structure of the exams vary by state, as education in Germany is managed by each state rather than by the federation.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Basic level exams may last up to four hours, e.g. the basic level math exam in Hamburg, while Advanced level exams may last up to six hours.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Oral exams can in many states be replaced by a presentation and a colloquium, taking a total of around 30 minutes.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Each semester of a subject studied in the final two years yields up to 15 points for a student, where advanced courses may count double, depending on the state.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The exact scoring system depends on the Bundesland in which one takes Abitur.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Passing the *Abitur* usually requires a composite score of at least 50%.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Students with a score below that minimum fail and do not receive an *Abitur*.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] There are some other conditions that the student also has to meet in order to receive the *Abitur*: taking mandatory courses in selected subject areas, and limits to the number of failing grades in core subjects.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Finally, students often have the option of omitting some courses from their composite score if they have taken more courses than the minimum required.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The best possible grade of 1.0 can be achieved if the score ranges between 823 and 900 points; the fraction of students achieving this score is normally only around 0.2%–3% even among the already selective population of *Abitur* candidates.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Around 12%–30% of *Abitur* candidates achieve grades between 1.0 and 1.9.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] Historically, very few people received their *Abitur* in Germany because many attractive jobs did not require one.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The number of persons holding the *Abitur* has steadily increased since the 1970s, and younger jobholders are more likely to hold the *Abitur* than older ones.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The percentage of students qualified for tertiary education is still lower than the OECD average.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The International Abitur is offered at schools outside Germany that are accredited by the German government.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The five Abitur exams (three written exams and two oral exams) are in the following subjects: German literature, European history or economics or mathematics or a natural science or a language.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In February of senior year (grade 12), all students take the written examinations for the German International Abitur in three subjects including German.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] In late spring, students have mandatory oral examinations in two subjects, which are overseen by a German educational official.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The final GPA includes grades from both junior and senior years, as well as for the five Abitur exams.
[src:anke-fuchs/abitur] The final diploma that students receive after successful completion of these exams allows them to qualify for admission to universities in Germany.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:anke-fuchs/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:anke-fuchs/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Adolf Spies von Büllesheim was born in Haus Hall in Ratheim, district of Heinsberg, in North Rhine-Westphalia, property of the baronial Spies von Büllesheim family since the 18th century.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] He was the son of Egon Franz Freiherr Spies von Büllesheim and his wife Maria (born Freiin von Oer).
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After school in Erkelenz he studied German law and farming at universities in Cologne and in Bonn.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After university he worked as a farmer and a lawyer from 1960 to 1997.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Since 1952 Spies von Büllesheim was a member of the CDU political party.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1969 to 1972 he was mayor of Hückelhoven.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1972 to 1987 Spies von Büllesheim was member of the German Bundestag for Heinsberg.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Spies von Büllesheim was married to Gräfin Maria Immaculata (born Concha) von Mirbach-Harff, Freiin von Vittinghoff (1938–2002), and together they had six children.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] CDU Hückelhoven.de: Die CDU Hückelhoven trauert um ihren Ehrenvorsitzenden Dr.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller joined the CDU in 1945 and was later elected to the state executive of the CDU Rhineland.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller was a member of the German Bundestag from 1961 to 1987.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] He had always entered parliament via the North Rhine-Westphalia state list.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] The social policy expert was Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour from 1965 to 1969 and Deputy Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs from 1969 to September 1981.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] From 1981 to 1987 he was deputy chairman of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group in the Bundestag.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] Born in Holzhausen, Homberg, Schmidt became a mechanic at a coal mine, then in 1942 was drafted into the navy as a submarine mechanic.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] He was taken as a prisoner of war and released at the end of the war, returning to the pit.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] In 1947, he joined the Union of Mining and Energy (IG BE), and immediately won election to the works council at the mine.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] In 1949, he joined the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), and the following year he studied in Frankfurt.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] In 1951, Schmidt began working full-time for IG BE, as its Munich youth secretary, then he successively ran the union's offices in Breisgau and Gießen, before in 1965 he became head of the union's Hesse-Rhineland-Palatinate district, and also won election to its executive.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] In 1969, Schmidt was elected as the president of IG BE, on a platform of improving working conditions in coal mines, and preserving jobs in coal mining and at nuclear power stations.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] In 1971, he was additionally elected as president of the Miners' International Federation, and in 1972 he was elected as an SPD member of the Bundestag.
[src:anke-fuchs/adolf-schmidt] Schmidt stood down from his international post in 1984, as president of the IG BE in 1985, and from the Bundestag in 1987.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] It later emerged that she had become entangled, as an industry lobbyist, in the CDU donations scandal.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The prosecutors' office in Düsseldorf launched an investigation against her in respect of allegations involving serious fraud, false statements and tax evasion, but by 2007 she was seriously ill and the case was suspended.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] It was dropped in 2008 on account of Hürland-Büning's "permanent incapacity to deal with matters" (*"wegen dauernder Verhandlungsunfähigkeit der Angeklagten"*).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Agnes Oleynik was born into a Roman Catholic family in Holsterhausen, a small town on the western fringes of Dorsten (into which it was formally subsumed in 1943), a mid-sized mining and industrial town north of Essen, a short distance to the east of the Dutch frontier and Nijmegen.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She was enrolled at the local Catholic school in 1932.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] War broke out when she was 13 and troops were stationed at the school: teaching immediately became more "irregular" (*"... sehr unregelmäßig"*), especially after the children were sent to take part in combined classes at one of the two nearby protestant schools.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She completed her schooling young, with others in her cohort, in the spring of 1940, and was conscripted into the Labour Service (*"Reichsarbeitsdienst"*).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She was later sent to work in a munitions factory.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] After war ended, in May 1945, she worked as a volunteer nurse before moving on to complete an apprenticeship as a carer at the "Westfalia Welfare College" (*"Westfälische Wohlfahrtsschule"*) in Münster.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Sources are for the most part silent about her marriage, but by 1960, when she returned to the labour market, it was as Agnes Hürland, the mother of four or five children.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She was employed, till 1968, as a secretary / senior support worker (*"Chefassistentin"*) with an industrial business.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She worked for two years for the national labour agency.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] After that there were two years as a rehabilitation counsellor.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] There are also references to her having worked as an insurance and real-estate broker (*"Immobilienmaklerin"*) during the 1960s and / or early 1970s.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] By 1969 her marriage had ended in divorce: there is a mention of her husband having been affected by alcoholism.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] After a brief flirtation with the centre-left Social Democratic Party (SPD) – "because I confused 'social' with 'social democratic'" – Agnes Hürland-Büning joined the centre-right CDU in 1964.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She served as a local councillor in Dorsten between 1969 and 1975, taking a particular interest in social policy.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Her career as a national politician started only when she was.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Her inclusion on the CDU candidate list for North Rhine-Westphalia resulted, according to one unsympathetic source, from the party's introduction of gender quotas.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] As a result, she found herself elected to the Bundestag in 1972.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Nationally the election result was a close one, and many commentators were surprised when, following coalition negotiations, the SPD's Willy Brandt returned to power as Chancellor, while the CDU remained in opposition.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning became a member of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs, in which she took a particular interest in to the needs of the disabled.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Helmut Kohl took over as CDU party leader in 1973.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Apart from her committee work she maintained a low profile in the Bundestag.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Kohl nevertheless valued her as a loyal party stalwart and when, in 1982, power finally passed to the CDU, Chancellor Kohl appointed her as "party business leader" (*" Fraktions-Geschäftsführerin"*) in the chamber.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She became known for her humanity, warmth, and willingness to reach out and make informal alliances with members of rival parties.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Even so, evidence of her political impact was limited.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Described by colleagues and observers – sometimes admiringly and sometimes disparagingly – as "the mother of the CDU/CSU party Bundestag group", one underwhelmed commentator suggested that she was at her happiest when organising the annual early summer asparagus lunch for the CDU Bundestag faction.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Directly after the 1987 election Chancellor Kohl made Hürland-Büning his secretary of state for defence.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She had no great specialist knowledge of defence matters, but many felt that her human qualities more than compensated for a lack of technical expertise.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Her grandmotherly manner, on display when she visited young recruits and junior officers, provided a reassuring picture.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Indeed, her appointment found support not just within the governing coalition parties but also from the SPD which was the principal opposition party.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She was the first woman to hold the post.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She paid particular attention to the welfare of the junior ranks.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] One development that she oversaw was a pilot project for the recruitment of female soldiers (on a volunteer basis).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She continued to enjoy a close political relationship with Helmut Kohl.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] In a prescient remark during a visit to the Knesset in Jerusalem she noted that if anyone could achieve German reunification, it was Helmut Kohl.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Commentators also note that her position within the Ministry of Defence meant that military contracts worth million of marks crossed Agnes Hürland-Büning's desk.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] 1990 was the year of German reunification, and the first general election of the newly unified country took place on 2 December 1990.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] By now approximately six months short of her sixty-fifth birthday, Hürland-Büning did not stand for re-election.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She accordingly retired from the Bundestag early in 1991, ahead of the new parliamentary session.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] She retired with her reputation in robust good order, awarded (among other honours) the Order of Merit (*"Große Bundesverdienstkreuz der Bundesrepublik"*) and the Order of Olga.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] However, the name of Agnes Hürland-Büning hit the headlines towards the end of that year in connection with the emerging CDU donations scandal: more details of her alleged involvement in those events, most of which dated back to 1992, appeared in Der Spiegel in January 2000.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning resigned her membership of the Weizsäcker Commission on 20 January 2000, a few days after the Spiegel piece appeared.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Her involvement in transferring members of the old East German People's Army to the Bundeswehr was also abruptly terminated when she was dismissed by means of a telephone call from Defences Minister Scharping.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] According to the report of a parliamentary committee of enquiry, after retiring from her position with the Ministry of Defence, Agnes Hürland-Büning concluded several high-value "dubious consultancy agreements".
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Just two of the agreements, those with Thyssen AG and Elf Aquitaine, yielded fees amounting to eight and a half or nine and a half million Marks.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] (Sources differ.) What she had to do for all this money never became entirely clear.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] However, investigators felt that this may have amounted, at best, to an incomplete explanation, especially given that eight years later the pipeline construction in question had never taken place, apparently for unrelated reasons.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators appear never fully to have plumbed the suspected depths of the so-called Leuna affair, which sources imply may have been focused not so much on the personal enrichment of top politicians as on the garnering of funds to cover the political expenses incurred by the CDU.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators felt that the massive fees received by Hürland-Büning were completely disproportionate to anything that she might have done to earn them.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] There was also widespread speculation that even if she had received the fees stated, it had never been intended that she should be the ultimate recipient.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The suspicion persisted that she had passed on the funds in the wider context of the Leuna affair and of the associated CDU donations scandal.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] One member of the parliamentary committee was Friedhelm Julius Beucher of the SPD.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] He described Hürland-Büning as a "living money-laundering system for the [Christian Democratic] Union (CDU).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] I think the lady's involvement was as the suitcase carrier" (*eine "lebende Geldwaschanlage der Union.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Ich glaube, die Dame war als Kofferträgerin aktiv."*).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] In the words of one commentator, the suspected contents of the suitcase were "black money for Kohl's black coffers" (*"schwarzes Geld für Kohls schwarze Kassen"*).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Nevertheless, it was clear from much of the media comment that many suspected that Hürland-Büning had also enriched herself along the way.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigations by the prosecutors' office were followed by the issuance of charges in December 2003.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Once her consultancy activities had been defined as a business it became liable for substantial arrears of unpaid business tax to the municipality.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] During her final years, with the threat of legal sanctions hanging over her, and a new generation of leaders controlling the CDU, there are indications that Hürland-Büning felt abandoned by those who had previously been friends.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Her former mentor Helmut Kohl increasingly withdrew from public life after the CDU donations scandal became public, especially following the tragic death of his first wife in 2001.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Within the little town of Dorsten there emerges a sense, from some sources, that family members and remaining friends felt that the work she had been able to do for individual citizens with problems, for Dorsten businesses, and for the town more generally, were all too quickly forgotten.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Meanwhile, at her criminal trial matters took a new twist in September 2004 when her defence lawyer submitted a doctor's certificate attesting that the 78 year old defendant's deteriorating health meant that she was no longer sufficiently fit to enable a fair trial take place.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Although it would take more than three more years for the court to reach a final decision in respect of the medical evidence, it was becoming increasingly likely that Agnes Hürland-Büning would go to the grave unconvicted but without her name ever being cleared.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] That was indeed the position on 9 March 2009 when she died following a major operation.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Only her family and a small number of close friends were present at her burial.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Her parliamentary colleagues were represented by a wreath that arrived from the Bundestag.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Since then she has been commemorated each year by a further wreath, sent on All Saints' Day, and decorated with the black/red/gold sash of the CDU/CSU, on behalf of her Bundestag former party colleagues and their successors in Berlin.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2011 insolvency proceedings were launched against the estate of Agnes Hürland-Büning in respect of around €200,000 in unpaid business taxes payable to the municipality of Dorsten at the time of her death.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] By 2011 the debt had been reduced to around €170,000 by means of monthly payments of €1,000.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The city maintained its claim for the balance through the bankruptcy.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The business tax claim by the municipality had already been the subject of major disagreements within the council as far back as 2002.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] At that point CDU councillors, with their controlling majority, had agreed to a compromise deal with their high-profile debtor, freezing the debt and hoping, by means of the agreement, at least to secure monthly repayments of €1,000.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] SPD and Green Party councillors had opposed the settlement while the FDP councillors had abstained in the vote.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The CDU share of the votes in the local council election slipped below 50% in 2009, although they remained the largest single party, with 22 of the 44 council seats.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2012, during an interview concerning the state of municipal finances, a reporter asked the Dorsten town treasurer – another CDU councillor – about the prospects of recovering the unpaid business taxes of former CDU Bundestag member Agnes Hürland-Büning.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The treasurer declined to speculate on how much money would become available at the conclusion of the insolvency proceedings.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Bundesautobahn 31 runs parallel with the Dutch frontier, linking Emden in the north with Bottrop to the south.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The section passing to the west of Dorsten was completed and opened in 1989.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Between Junctions 37 and 38 there is an unmarked junction, without signage and without a junction number.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The unmarked junction was not included in the plans for the road, and only those with local knowledge are aware that it can be accessed by leaving or joining the Autobahn where maps and signs indicate a parking area ("Parkplatz Dorsten-Holsterhausen").
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The limited access junction only permits traffic to join the Autobahn in a southerly direction, towards Bottrop (and, indirectly, Bonn) or to leave the Autobahn travelling north (from Bottrop and, indirectly, Bonn).
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The rumour gained added traction after the name of the former secretary of state began to appear in press reports connecting her with the CDU donations scandal.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Der Spiegel gave it national coverage in 2000 and repeated it in 2002.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2009 the pupils in class 9a at the Gymnasium St.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Ursula (secondary school) undertook what turned out to be an award winning investigation into the origins of the *"Hürlandausfahrt"*.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Arnold Erwig, their politics teacher, admitted that at the outset he had always assumed the rumours were true.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Only a few were prepared to have their voices recorded.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The town council had indeed objected to the Autobahn plans which had specified a junction at the hamlet of Schembeck, to the north, and a junction at Dorsten-West, some distance to the south.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] The city father demanded an extra Autobahn junction, but without success.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] They then invoked their local representative in the Bundestag.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Through her relationship with Chancellor Kohl, it turned out that Agnes Hürland-Büning did enjoy more influence with the transport planners than might have been expected.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Even her lobbying powers were not sufficient to provide for a complete additional junction, but the unmarked junction, accessible through the parking area, represented a compromise for which the city council at the time was appreciative.
[src:anke-fuchs/agnes-hürland-büning] Those with the necessary local knowledge were able to save themselves time by using the "secret" junction: at the time that did indeed includes Agnes Hürland-Büning herself.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She was born Anke Nevermann in Hamburg, the daughter of Paul Nevermann who later became mayor of Hamburg, and his wife Grete.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] Her parents met at home politicians such as Herbert Wehner, Kurt Schumacher, Wilhelm Pieck and Otto Grotewohl.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] Her parents, both grandfathers and two brothers were party members of the Social Democratic Party (SPD).
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She joined the party's youth organisation (*Falken*) as a school student, and was active in demonstrations against atomic weapons.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She became a party member in 1956, shortly before her Abitur.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] The same year, she began to study law, completing with the Zweites Staatsexamen in 1964.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She then worked as Referentin für Arbeitsrecht und Sozialpolitik for Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund (DGB) for the Nordmark district.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She was member of the board of the IG Metall from 1971 to 1978.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] In 1977, Fuchs was appointed Secretary of State in the Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs by the then minister Herbert Ehrenberg.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] In 1979, she became a member of the board (*Parteivorstand*) of the SPD.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She was elected to the Bundestag in 1980 as a candidate from the Cologne II district in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] On 28 April 1982, Fuchs was appointed Federal Minister for Youth, Family and Health by Chancellor Helmut Schmidt.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] Following the election victory of the conservative opposition, she had to leave the cabinet on 4 October 1982.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She was offered candidacy for minister-president in Lower Saxony in the 1980s, but declined in favour of Gerhard Schröder.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] In 1990, she was the SPD candidate for the position in Saxony, but the CDU with Kurt Biedenkopf won the election.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] Fuchs was a member of the Bundestag until 2002.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She was vice president of its SPD fraction from 1993 to 1998, and she served as Vice President of the Bundestag from 1998 to 2002.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] For many years she was president of the Deutscher Mieterbund (German tenants' association), and she was president of the Friedrich Ebert Foundation from 2003 to 2010.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She focused on national and international political education, support of young scientists in international cooperation, and European politics for peace and social reforms.
[src:anke-fuchs/anke-fuchs] She died on 14 October 2019 after a long illness, at the age of 82.
